text: I believe it may be for the same reason I could and could not get along with some of the actors my mother used to work with on a little Disney TV show known as "Girl Meets World." A lot of the cast were cool people and I could get along well and hold casual conversation with no problems. I got along really well with most of the cast aside from Rowan Blanchard. for the life of me I could not find anything to speak to her about because she always had a certain off-putting response she would have for most topics or things. Most notably I made a comment about something Corey was doing in-between takes and said something back,  then, out of nowhere, and for almost no reason, Rowan piped up something along the lines of, "See, men are always looking at us like we're inferior to them. We need to do something about this." For some of the people on that set there was little you could use to hold a normal conversation with her, especially if you were a dude, that was the main reason I could not speak to her, and what a lot of people dislike Emma Watson and Gal Gadot, they're female empowerment figures. this is not something I don't support, but at a certain point if you keep pushing female empowerment down the throats of people it starts to get a very off-putting taste to it, and it alienates a lot of the people you know.

"Gonna" is at least acknowledged as an informal word by Webster's, although it's still not a real word. "Imma" or "Ima" is not. They're ebonics, which glorifies being illiterate. Other examples are saying "axe" instead of ask and "finna" instead of fixing to or going to. 

Black people use this slang to show their blackness (IMO) and white people use these words to sound like they're hood. It's dumb really. People should be proud to be smart, not proud to be (act) illiterate. Just more dumbing down of America.

Rant/explanation over.

text: Israel has had many names throughout history that go back thousands of years. What you called it most likely depended on where your place is in history and geographical location were at the time. For Jews it has always been the Jewish land since the start of the culture, and for other people it may have had other names according to their claim. So going back is very  complicated, but even just going back a hundred years doesn't resolve the conflict, because the land was under Ottoman Empire till the empire fell in the early 1900, after that the land was divided between the British mandate and French rule. Syria, Lebanon, Jordan and Egypt did not exist as independent states yet. There are Jews that never left Israel after the Roman conquer around 150 BC and stayed in the four holly cities under various empires for over 2,000 years, and of course Arabs also lived on the land, though Islam only forged in 1,500 years ago, so they weren't muslim yet, though some may have been christian. During the 1900's immigration to Israel from both Jewish and Arab nations picked up. During that time a lot of land was bought from rich Syrian/Jordanian landlords by Jewish organizations and individuals, the Arab tenants of those lands (bare in mind most people didn't own land at the time) were then asked to leave. No land was taken by force before the war of 1948 when Syria, Lebanon, Jordan and Egypt did not accept the UN's devision of land, which was actually in favor of the Arabs (giving them a much bigger part), during that war some land where Arabs lived was confiscated by Israel though not all. After that war the West Bank actually became part of Jordan and Gaza was a part of Egypt, until they waged war against Israel in 1967. After that war those parts became part of Israel again with the addition of Sinai, which was returned to Egypt in a Peace treaty in 1979, they did not want the Gaza strip in that agreement though it was offered. In the peace treaty with Jordan they also got land back, though not the West Bank. There were no walls or borders between the West Bank and Israel until the 1990's when a wave of terrorist attacks were carried out by the Fatah and Hamas who still rule in the West Bank and Gaza. There are many Arabs that live inside Israel as Israeli citizen, 15-20% of the population actually, they vote and get subsidizes education and health care like every other citizen.  Inside Israel they do not refer to themselves as Palestinian. The name Palestinian did not necessarily define the Arabs that lived in that land, some may have been citizens of the Ottoman Empire, or the other states that were established around the same time as Israel. But it doesn't matter, if they wish to be called Palestinian than that's enough to justify the name, but if that name were to be used to describe those who lived on that land before Israel's declaration of independence that the Jews of Hebron and Zefat and Tiberias and Jerusalem would also be called Palestinian, which would also be inaccurate cause they all lived under various Empires depending on the era.  So we're left with what to do today, it would be inaccurate to say Israel belonged to the Palestinians, cause it didn't, but that doesn't mean they don't have a right to live there. The best solution would be a two state solution, where each nation has their own piece of the land. Living together is not a good option considering the history and the fact that there were terrorist against jews by Arabs way before the establishment of Israel. Also, side note, the proximity of the West Bank and Gaza to Israel is so close that it would be impossible to use chemical weapons without effecting both peoples, so let's put that lie to rest.
